  <h1 class="article__title reveal">Designing with AI: Where UX Meets Machine Learning</h1>

  <p class="reveal">
    The conversation around AI in design often focuses on tools — which AI can generate
    layouts, write copy, or produce images. But the more interesting question is about
    the experiences themselves: how do we design interactions with AI that feel natural,
    trustworthy, and genuinely useful?
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    As interaction designers, we have a unique responsibility in this space. We're the ones
    shaping how people experience these powerful systems. And that means thinking beyond
    the interface to the underlying mental models, expectations, and emotional responses
    that AI-powered products create.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The Design Challenge of Uncertainty</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Traditional interfaces are deterministic — press a button, get a predictable result.
    AI introduces probabilistic outcomes, and that fundamentally changes the design contract
    with users. How do you design for a system that might be wrong? How do you build trust
    when outputs vary?
  </p>

  <blockquote class="reveal">
    The best AI experiences don't hide the machine — they create a transparent partnership
    between human judgment and computational capability.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 class="reveal">What Interaction Designers Bring to the Table</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Our training in user research, information architecture, and interaction patterns is
    exactly what AI products need. We know how to ask the right questions about user needs,
    how to structure complex information clearly, and how to design feedback loops that
    help people understand and control the systems they use.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Designing with AI, not just for AI</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    There's a distinction that gets lost in most conversations about AI and design.
    Designing <em>for</em> AI means crafting experiences where the AI is the product —
    chatbots, recommendation engines, generative interfaces. But designing <em>with</em>
    AI means using it as a tool in your own process. And that changes how you work in
    ways that go far beyond efficiency.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    When I was working on <a href="/portfolio/kate-kbc/">Kate at KBC</a>, I was doing both
    simultaneously. I was designing the conversation experience — 186 dialogues, each one
    a careful balance of helpfulness and honesty about what the system could and couldn't
    do. But I was also the first designer on the team to explore integrating LLMs into
    what had been a fully rule-based chatbot. That meant understanding how the models
    worked well enough to know where they'd help and where they'd hallucinate.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The validation loop gets shorter</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    The most practical shift I've experienced is in prototyping speed. Tools like Claude
    Code, Cursor, and Replit let a designer go from concept to functional prototype in
    hours instead of days. Not a clickable Figma mockup — an actual working thing that
    people can use.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    This portfolio site is a concrete example. I built it with Claude Code — every page,
    every animation, every interaction. The design decisions and the implementation
    happened in the same conversation. There was no handoff, no spec document, no
    waiting for a dev sprint. When something didn't feel right, I changed it immediately
    and saw the result.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    You can't fully understand why something's broken until you use it and it actually
    breaks. AI tools compress that loop. You can put something in front of a real user
    that behaves like software, not just looks like it — and much earlier in the process.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What this means for interaction designers</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    I think the designers who will thrive in this landscape aren't the ones who resist
    AI or treat it as a threat to their craft. They're the ones who see it as a new
    material to work with — unpredictable, powerful, and demanding of thoughtful design.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    Our training in user research, feedback loops, and information architecture is
    exactly what AI products need. But now we can also use AI to strengthen our own
    process: pressure testing our thinking, generating variations, reasoning through
    edge cases at a speed that wasn't possible before.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    Designers who understand AI don't just design for it — they use it to collapse
    the gap between idea and implementation. That's what it means to be a
    <a href="/blog/block-shaped-designer/">block-shaped designer</a> in the age of AI.
  </p>
